            <fr:route>Complex integral.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Complex integral">Complex integral</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>25</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Recall the <fr:link type="local" href="Riemann%20integral.xml" addr="Riemann integral" title="Riemann integral">Riemann integral</fr:link> of a real function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: [a,b] \longrightarrow  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>This extends to the case when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: [a,b] \longrightarrow  \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f = \alpha  + i\beta ]]></fr:tex> in a natural way:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\int _a^b{\alpha  (t) + i\beta (t)}dt = \int _a^b{\alpha  (t)}dt + i\int _a^b{\beta (t)}dt]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>This integral satisfies <fr:link type="local" href="integration%20by%20parts.xml" addr="integration by parts" title="Integration by parts">integration by parts</fr:link> and also</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\left | \int _a^b{f(z)dz} \right | \leq  \int _a^b{\left | f(z)\right |dz }]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>We now introduce a new notion of integral for functions</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: E \subset  \mathbb {C} \longrightarrow  \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Definition</fr:strong> Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E \subset  \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> be open and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: E \longrightarrow  \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> be continuous.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma : [a,b] \longrightarrow  E]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C^1]]></fr:tex> curve, then we define the integral of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> along <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma ]]></fr:tex> as</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\int _\gamma  f = \int _a^b{f(\gamma (t)) \gamma '(t)}dt]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>The definition extends to the case when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma ]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>piecewise</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C^1]]></fr:tex> in the natural way (i.e. we integrate f on each part where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma ]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C^1]]></fr:tex> and then add up)</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Remark</fr:strong>: The integral of f can be written in terms of <fr:link type="external" href="differential%20form">differential form</fr:link>s</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f = u+iv]]></fr:tex> , <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma  = \gamma _1(t) + i\gamma _2(t)]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\int _\gamma  f = \int _a^b{\left ( u(\gamma (t)) \gamma _1'(t) - v(\gamma (t)) \gamma _2'(t)\right )}dt + i\int _a^b{\left ( u(\gamma (t)) \gamma _2'(t) + v(\gamma (t)) \gamma _1'(t) \right )}dt]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>Introdduce the <fr:link type="external" href="differential%20form">differential form</fr:link></fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\omega _R = u(x,y)dx - v(x,y)dy]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\omega _I = u(x,y)dy + v(x,y)dx]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>So</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\int _\gamma  f = \int _\gamma  \omega _R + i\int _\gamma  \omega _I]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Remark</fr:strong>: Note that this is not the regular <fr:link type="local" href="Line%20Integral.xml" addr="Line Integral" title="Line Integral">Line Integral</fr:link> in real analysis</fr:p>
            <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is a function of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> variables, then its line integral is defined as</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\int _{\gamma } {f(x)ds} = \int _a^b {f{(\gamma (t))} |\gamma '(t)| dt}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>This is different from the definition of complex integral. However one can see that</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\left | \int _\gamma  {f(z) dz} \right | \leq  \int _a^b{\left | f(z) \right | ds  = \int _a^b {|f{(\gamma (t))|} |\gamma '(t)| dt}}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Remark</fr:strong>: The integral <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\int _\gamma  f]]></fr:tex> does not depend on the <fr:link type="external" href="parameterization">parameterization</fr:link>, but the curve <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma ]]></fr:tex> <fr:strong>is</fr:strong> defined with an <fr:link type="external" href="orientation">orientation</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>If we change the orientation, then the integral changes its sign:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\int _{\gamma ^+} {f dz} = -\int _{\gamma ^-} {f dz}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>(This is the same case with Riemann integral)</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
